<section id="invariants">
  <h1>SpacetimeDB: Design &amp; External Services</h1>
  <p class="lead">An architectural perspective on maintaining the invariants SpacetimeDB is built on, while integrating non-deterministic external services such as LLM inference.</p>

  <h2>Design Invariants</h2>
  <p>SpacetimeDB's architecture rests on three properties that are not merely implementation details — they are the load-bearing walls of the system. Understanding them is necessary before asking what can or cannot be done within them.</p>

  <div class="cards">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="icon">⚙️</div>
      <div class="title">Determinism</div>
      <div class="desc">Given the same inputs, a reducer must always produce the same state change. This is what makes replication and consensus possible without coordination overhead.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="icon">⚛️</div>
      <div class="title">Atomicity</div>
      <div class="desc">Each reducer call is a transaction. It either commits fully or not at all. There is no partial state, and no rollback after a side effect has already escaped.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="icon">🔒</div>
      <div class="title">Isolation</div>
      <div class="desc">Reducers run inside a WASM sandbox with no ambient I/O. The only way data enters the system is through reducer arguments; the only way it leaves is through table writes.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Why these three together</strong>
    Determinism enables replication. Atomicity enables consistency. Isolation enforces both. Remove any one and the other two break down. An HTTP call inside a reducer would violate all three simultaneously.
  </div>

