<section id="reducer-gate">
  <h2>The Reducer as Logic Gate</h2>
  <p>There is a subtle but important clarification about how data enters SpacetimeDB. Clients do not <em>send data to be stored</em> — they <em>invoke reducers</em>. The reducer is the logic gate that decides whether and how that call becomes a state change.</p>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>Common misconception</strong>
    "The client sends a payload and the database stores it" implies raw data flows in. In SpacetimeDB, the client calls a named reducer with arguments. What gets written — and whether anything gets written at all — is entirely determined by the reducer's logic.
  </div>

  <p>This means the pre-storage processing you described is not a separate middleware concern. The reducer <em>is</em> that middleware. Validation, transformation, authorization, derived computations — all of this belongs in the reducer, because that is the only place state transitions are authorized to happen.</p>

