<section id="external-problem">
  <h2>The External Service Problem</h2>
  <p>If all application logic is meant to live inside the database, where does an LLM inference call go? It cannot go in a reducer — not as a technical workaround limitation, but because it would violate all three design invariants simultaneously:</p>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Invariant</th>
      <th>Why an inline HTTP call breaks it</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Determinism</strong></td>
      <td>Two replicas running the same reducer with the same inputs could receive different LLM responses. Consensus breaks.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Atomicity</strong></td>
      <td>If the reducer writes state and <em>then</em> calls an LLM which times out, the transaction cannot cleanly roll back an effect that already left the system.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Isolation</strong></td>
      <td>The WASM sandbox exists specifically to prevent ambient I/O. Bypassing it would undermine the entire execution model.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <p>The question then becomes: if the invariants are non-negotiable, is there a way to integrate external services without betraying the design?</p>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>The real question</strong>
    This is not about "getting around a limitation." It is about recognizing that LLM inference is not a transaction — it is <em>data acquisition</em>. The distinction determines where in the system it belongs.
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="why-not-client">
  <h2>Why Not the Client?</h2>
  <p>The instinct to reject the client as the home for LLM calls is architecturally sound, but the reasoning deserves precision. The objection is not that clients <em>cannot</em> make LLM calls — they can. The objection is about where <em>consequential decisions</em> should originate.</p>

  <p>In a game context: if the AI's decision (which unit to spawn, where to attack) is computed by the client and then submitted as a reducer call, then the client is trusted to compute it correctly and honestly. In a multiplayer or authoritative-server model, that trust is often unacceptable. A cheating client could submit any action, bypassing the AI decision entirely.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>The distinction</strong>
    The issue is not <em>who</em> makes the HTTP call. It is <em>who is trusted to reason about the result</em>. If the AI's decisions must be authoritative — not forgeable by a client — they cannot originate on the client.
  </div>

  <p>This is why the answer is not "put the LLM call on the client." It's also not "put the LLM call in the reducer." The answer requires a third participant: a <strong>server-side worker</strong> that is trusted but runs outside the WASM sandbox.</p>
</section>

