<section id="intent-result">
  <h2>The Intent–Result Pattern</h2>
  <p>The correct architectural pattern is a two-phase commit of intent and result, sometimes called the <strong>Oracle Pattern</strong> (analogous to how blockchain systems handle off-chain data). The key insight is that the database only ever receives <em>deterministic inputs</em> — the non-determinism is quarantined to a specific, acknowledged boundary outside the database.</p>

  <div class="steps">
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="label">Client invokes a reducer <span class="tag tag-wasm">wasm</span></div>
        <div class="detail">e.g. <code>request_ai_action(context)</code>. The reducer records an <em>intent row</em> with status <code>PENDING</code>. This is a fully deterministic, atomic write. No external call is made. The transaction commits immediately.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="label">Worker subscribes and detects the intent <span class="tag tag-native">native</span></div>
        <div class="detail">A server-side process (Rust, native binary) holds a SpacetimeDB client subscription. It observes the new <code>PENDING</code> row via a live subscription callback. The worker is co-located with the SpacetimeDB host — not the game client.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="label">Worker makes the external call <span class="tag tag-ext">external</span></div>
        <div class="detail">The worker calls the LLM API (via Rig, tokio, etc.). This is explicitly the non-deterministic boundary. If it fails, it retries or records a failure. No database state has been mutated yet for this event.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <div class="step-body">
        <div class="label">Worker submits the result via a reducer <span class="tag tag-wasm">wasm</span></div>
        <div class="detail">e.g. <code>record_ai_result(intent_id, action)</code>. The result is now a deterministic input. The reducer applies whatever logic is needed (validation, game-state consequences), and commits. The system is back to fully deterministic territory.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

