<section id="boundary">
  <h2>The Non-Determinism Boundary</h2>
  <p>The most important concept in this pattern is that the non-determinism boundary is <em>explicit and acknowledged</em>, not hidden or worked around. The worker is not a hack — it is a recognized architectural role: a <strong>trusted data provider</strong>.</p>

  <p>This is analogous to how financial systems handle market data. The exchange is authoritative over trades (like SpacetimeDB over game state), but it accepts price feeds from external data providers (like the worker providing LLM responses). The database never calls out; it receives. All external data arrives as a named, typed, traceable reducer call.</p>

  <div class="callout ok">
    <strong>The invariants are preserved</strong>
    The LLM response, once submitted to the <code>record_ai_result</code> reducer, is treated as a deterministic input. Every replica sees the same argument. The reducer applies the same logic. State converges. The database has no knowledge that the input was non-deterministically produced — and it does not need to.
  </div>

  <h3>What the worker is and is not</h3>
  <p>The worker is <strong>not</strong> application logic. It does not decide what the game does — that is still the reducer's job. The worker's only responsibility is to obtain a piece of data (the LLM response) and deliver it to the database. It is a data pipeline node, not a logic tier.</p>

  <p>This means: if someone asked "where does the game logic live?", the honest answer is still "in SpacetimeDB, in reducers." The worker is infrastructure — analogous to a message queue consumer or a webhook listener. Its logic is limited to: fetch, retry on failure, submit result.</p>
</section>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="app-logic">
  <h2>Where Logic Lives</h2>
  <p>Clarifying the distinction between application logic and data acquisition resolves the apparent tension in the original question.</p>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Concern</th>
      <th>Category</th>
      <th>Where it belongs</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Validate a unit spawn request</td>
      <td>Application logic</td>
      <td class="yes">Reducer (SpacetimeDB)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Compute damage from an attack</td>
      <td>Application logic</td>
      <td class="yes">Reducer (SpacetimeDB)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Respond to an AI decision</td>
      <td>Application logic</td>
      <td class="yes">Reducer (SpacetimeDB)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Decide what AI action to take</td>
      <td>Data acquisition (non-det)</td>
      <td style="color: var(--warn); font-weight: 600;">Worker → submits to reducer</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Call LLM inference API</td>
      <td>External I/O</td>
      <td style="color: var(--warn); font-weight: 600;">Worker only</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Render game state</td>
      <td>Presentation</td>
      <td class="no">Client only</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <p>Notice that "responding to" an AI decision is application logic (reducer), while "deciding" is data acquisition (worker). The boundary falls between having the data and acting on it — not between game logic and AI logic.</p>
</section>

