  <h3>The key optimization</h3>
  <p>The expensive leg is always the LLM API call — hundreds of milliseconds regardless of architecture. The client's experience is: <em>call reducer, wait for a subscription update when the AI result is committed</em>. That wait is dominated by the LLM latency, not by the worker's internal hops. Co-locating the worker with the SpacetimeDB host ensures the worker→database round-trip is sub-millisecond and does not compound the LLM latency.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>What the client actually experiences</strong>
    The client sends one reducer call. It then waits on a subscription, which fires when <code>record_ai_result</code> commits. From the client's perspective, this is indistinguishable from the database having computed the result itself — except the client made a single, clean call and received a reactive update. No polling. No second request.
  </div>

  <h3>Summary</h3>
  <p>The Intent–Result pattern does not compromise SpacetimeDB's design invariants — it works with them. The database remains the authoritative, deterministic system it is designed to be. The worker is an acknowledged infrastructure role: a data provider, not a logic tier. Application logic stays in reducers. Non-determinism stays isolated and explicit. And from the client's perspective, the system behaves as if the database computed the AI response itself.</p>
</section>

